In all seriousness, I was getting playable framerates running windowed, with the god rays and FSAA turned off, with unimpressive hardware. An i7-2600 with 16GB of DDR3 and an RX550 4GB card generally handled it playably.

I recently upgraded for DCS World, still with old-ish and not-high-end hardware. Ryzen 5 3600 with 48GB DDR4 3200 and a kind of weird video card I found are handling it great. RX6600M. The card is built on a new PCB, using a GPU pulled out of an unsold gaming laptop, with 8GB of GDDR6. It gives 95-100% of the performance of a normal RX6600 in almost every benchmark, with much less heat and power draw. And unlike the nVidia gaming laptop chip bootleg graphics cards, it has official driver support. MSC runs really well on it, even fullscreen. It struggles here and there with DCS World, even with almost all the eye candy turned way down. But it's better than the 550 was.
